{
  "answer": "In Mirza Ghalib's ghazal, the bulbul (nightingale) embodies the lover's ardent, futile devotion to the beloved (figured as the indifferent rose). A canonical couplet captures this:\n\n> How slain we are by the false grace of the rose;  \n> The bulbul's labor meets the laughing face of the rose.[^1]\n\nGhalib's bulbul *sings*—its \"labor\" is the traditional nightingale song of passionate longing—but registers the speaker's (the lover's) bitter awareness of rejection and the cruelty of unrequited love.[^2]\n\nIn Allama Iqbal's \"Parinde ki Faryad\" (\"A Bird's Lament\"), the bird (parinda, a generic fowl trapped in a cage) voices explicit captivity and collective anguish, distinguishing its voice from song:\n\n> O listener, don't think this a song and be glad,  \n> It is the cry of all hearts that are wounded and sad.[^3]\n\nIqbal's bird *complains* (faryad)—a desperate plea for release from imprisonment, as in its closing supplication: \"O Captor, I beg you, now make me unbound, / I'm voiceless; release me, a blessing you've found.\"[^4] This registers the speaker's (the bird's, as proxy for the oppressed ummah or individual soul) profound sense of alienation, lost freedom, and shared human suffering under constraint.[^5]\n\n[^1]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, [paragraph](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/62-hai-kis-qadar-halaak-e-fareb-e-wafa-e-gul/translation/#p-f96105).\n\n[^2]: Ibid., ch. 62 (full ghazal). [Chapter](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/62-hai-kis-qadar-halaak-e-fareb-e-wafa-e-gul/translation/).\n\n[^3]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/34-parinde-ki-faryad/translation/#p-7d35b0).\n\n[^4]: Ibid., [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/34-parinde-ki-faryad/translation/#p-983c20).\n\n[^5]: Ibid., ch. 34 (full poem). [Chapter](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/34-parinde-ki-faryad/translation/).",
